ng="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230826_wot216.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><figure> <span itemscope="" itemprop="image" itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject" data-slim="0"><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/2728/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png" srcset="https://www.economist.com/img/b/200/426/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 200w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/300/639/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 300w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/400/853/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 400w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/600/1279/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 600w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/640/1364/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 640w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/800/1705/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 800w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1000/2131/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 1000w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/2728/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230826_wof216.png 1280w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 640px, 95vw" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></span></figure><p class="article__body-text"><span>过去一年，美国经济的成功依赖于三大支柱：健康的劳动力市场、通胀下降以及疫情期间积累的储蓄推动的强劲支出。这最后一个支柱可能开始让位。旧金山联邦储备银行的哈姆扎·阿卜杜勒拉赫曼 (Hamza Abdelrahman) 和路易斯·奥利维拉 (Luiz Oliveira) 的研究表明，美国人已经消耗掉了 2020 年和 2021 年积累的 90% 以上的“超额储蓄”。经济学家估计，剩下的可能是九月底就消失了。</span></p><p class="article__body-text"><span>在大流行期间，刺激支票和其他政府支持使个人收入增加了 1 万美元以上，而封锁限制又使美国人的支出减少了 1 万美元。结果，每月个人储蓄占收入的比例从 2019 年的 9% 左右飙升至 2020 年春季的 30% 以上。</span></p><p class="article__body-text"><span>但政府机构经济分析局的数据显示，到 2022 年 6 月，美国的个人储蓄率已骤降至仅 2.7%。尽管此后该比率略有上升（6 月份家庭将收入的 4.3% 存入储蓄库），但仍远低于大流行前的水平。</span></p> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 22 Aug 2023 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/phkkqjq2j455o4qf1e279gv5v2r91fj5</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/espressochart/2023<category>不确定</category><category>联合国</category><category>刚果民主共和国</category><category>埃塞俄比亚</category><category>印度</category><category>尼日利亚</category><category>巴基斯坦</category><category>中国</category><category>人口增长</category></item></channel></rss>